# GTD Architecture and Principles

## Architecture Direction

- Use feature-first structure for new MVP areas: `src/features/capture`, `src/features/clarify`, `src/features/engage`, `src/features/projects`, `src/features/review`.
- Keep domain types centralized in `src/types/gtd.ts`; avoid duplicating entity shapes in feature folders.
- Treat `src/hooks/useBoardState.ts` as temporary orchestration only; extract pure selectors/transitions to reusable helpers when logic grows.
- Persist user data locally first (versioned snapshot + migration-safe loading), then evolve adapters if needed.

## GTD Domain Invariants (Must Hold)

- `Item` is raw capture only: at capture time it contains only raw fields (`id`, `title`, `notes`, `createdAt`, `source`, `clarified`).
- Clarify is mandatory before execution: raw inbox lists only `clarified === false`.
- Clarify outcomes for MVP are only: `next_action`, `project`, `someday`, `trash`.
- Every active `Project` must have at least one active `NextAction`.
- Engage views show actionable work by real constraints (context first), not by artificial priority.

## State and Data Rules

- Prefer explicit transition functions over ad-hoc object mutation.
- Add storage version bumps for breaking shape changes and provide fallback for invalid or stale snapshots.
- Keep derived data in selectors (`inboxItems`, `visibleNextActions`, `projectsWithoutNextAction`) rather than storing duplicates in state.
- Use stable IDs and timestamps for all GTD entities; never regenerate IDs during migration.

## UI and Composition Rules

- UI should reduce thinking friction and push completion, not over-organization.
- Do not build reusable UI primitives inside `src/`; use `design-system` components for reusable widgets.
- For one-off feature UI, colocate presentational components inside the feature folder.
- Clarify and Weekly Review flows must be keyboard-usable and explicit about next required action.

## Implementation Principles

- Build in thin vertical slices: `data -> state -> ui -> validation -> manual-test`.
- Keep old behavior working during migration; avoid big-bang rewrites.
- Prefer small, reversible changes and explicit guards for invalid transitions.

## Examples

```typescript
// ✅ Good: transition is explicit and validates invariant.
if (project.status === 'active' && projectNextActions.length === 0) {
  throw new Error('Active project requires at least one next action')
}
```

```typescript
// ❌ Bad: silently mutates status without checking GTD rules.
project.status = 'active'
```
